                                    </div>
                                    <p class="has-medium-font-size">Erector Spinae</p>
                                    <p class="has-small-font-size"><p><span data-sheets-root="\&quot;1\&quot;" data-sheets-value="\&quot;{&quot;1&quot;:2,&quot;2&quot;:&quot;Muscles" data-sheets-userformat="\&quot;{&quot;2&quot;:769,&quot;3&quot;:{&quot;1&quot;:0},&quot;11&quot;:3,&quot;12&quot;:0}\&quot;">Muscles that span the entire length of your spine on either side.</span></p></p>
                                </div>
                                                            <div class="secondary-item muscle-item">
                                    <div class="muscle-img">
                                        <img src="https://www.endomondo.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Upper-Rectus-Abdominis.png" alt="">
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="has-medium-font-size">Upper Rectus Abdominis</p>
                                    <p class="has-small-font-size"><p>Muscles located just below the lower chest and above the lower abdominals. Between your ribs and pubic bone.</p></p>
                                </div>
                                                            <div class="secondary-item muscle-item">
                                    <div class="muscle-img">
                                        <img src="https://www.endomondo.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Middle-Trapezius.png" alt="">
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="has-medium-font-size">Middle Trapezius</p>
                                    <p class="has-small-font-size"><p>Muscles located in the middle of your back between your upper and lower traps.</p></p>
                                </div>
